{"title_page": "Andrew H. Cozzens", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix= [[Excellency|His Excellency]], [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name        = Andrew Harmon Cozzens\n| title       = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|Auxiliary Bishop of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]<br>Titular Bishop of [[Africa (Roman province)|Bisica]]\n| image       = Bishop_Cozzens_with_Two_Deacons.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Bishop Cozzens with two deacons\n| church      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]\n| diocese     = \n| see         = \n| appointed   = October 11, 2013\n| enthroned   = December 9, 2013\n| predecessor = \n| successor   =\n| other_post  = Titular Bishop of [[Africa (Roman province)|Bisica]]\n\n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = May 3, 1997\n| ordinated_by   = \n| consecration   = December 9, 2013\n| consecrated_by = [[John Clayton Nienstedt]], [[Harry Joseph Flynn]], and [[Paul Sirba]]\n| rank           = \n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1968|8|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Denver, Colorado]] \n| death_date    =\n| death_place   = \n| previous_post =\n| coat_of_arms  = \n| motto         = PR\u00c6BE NOBIS COR TUUM\n}}\n\n{{Infobox bishopstyles  \n| name=  Andrew Harmon Cozzens\n| dipstyle=  \n*[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n*[[The Most Reverend]]    \n| offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] \n| relstyle=[[Bishop]] \n| image = Coat_of_arms_of_Andrew_Harmon_Cozzens.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Harmon Cozzens''', (August 3, 1968) is a [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|bishop]] of the [[Catholic Church]] in the [[United States]].  Since 2013 he has been an [[auxiliary bishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|Saint Paul and Minneapolis]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nAndrew Cozzens was born on August 3, 1968, in [[Denver|Denver, Colorado]] to Jack and Judy Cozzens.<ref>{{cite web |title=Auxiliary bishop named for Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis |url=http://thecatholicspirit.com/featured/auxiliary-bishop-named-archdiocese-saint-paul-minneapolis/ |website=The Catholic Spirit |publisher=The Catholic Spirit |accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref> Andrew Cozzens attended [[Benedictine College]] in [[Atchison, Kansas]], graduating in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clawson |first1=Makena |title=Newly elected bishop, Andrew Cozzens, Raven alum \u2013 The Circuit |url=http://benedictinecircuit.com/bishop-elect-andrew-cozzens-raven-bishop/ |website=Benedictine Circuit |accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref> During his time at Benedictine College, he helped found the college's pro-life student group and a charismatic prayer group. In 1990, he was arrested several times for blocking access to abortion clinics and served several weeks in jail.<ref>{{cite web |title=State v. Cozzens |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/nebraska/supreme-court/1992/494-7.html |website=Justia Law |accessdate=25 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiering |first1=Maria |title=Bishop fields queries on vocations, jail time in Google Hangout |url=http://thecatholicspirit.com/news/local-news/bishop-fields-queries-on-vocations-jail-time-in-google-hangout/ |website=TheCatholicSpirit.com |publisher=The Catholic Spirit |accessdate=25 February 2019 |date=25 November 2015}}</ref> After a period of discernment, including a time serving as a missionary with [[NET Ministries]] in 1991-1992, he entered the [[Saint Paul Seminary School of Divinity]].\n\n===Priestly ministry===\nCozzens was ordained a priest in 1997 for the Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis and served as the associate pastor at the [[Cathedral of Saint Paul (Minnesota)|Cathedral of St. Paul]] from 1997\u20132000 and at Divine Mercy Parish from 2000 to 2002. He earned a S.T.L. from the [[Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas|Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas, ''Angelicum'']] in Rome, Italy in 2002 and began full time doctoral studies in 2002. He earned his S.T.D. in 2008 with a dissertation entitled ''Imago vivens Iesu Christi sponsi Ecclesiae : the priest as a living image of Jesus Christ the Bridegroom of the Church through the evangelical counsels.'' In 2006, he began as an assistant professor of sacramental theology and the director of liturgy at the Saint Paul Seminary School of Divinity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archspm.org/news-events/news-detail.php?intResourceID=10191|title=Reverend Andrew Cozzens Named Auxiliary Bishop of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> He remained there until he was named a bishop.\n\n===Episcopal ministry===\nCozzens was appointed titular Bishop of Bisica and an auxiliary for the Archbishop of Saint Paul and Minneapolis on October 11, 2013 by [[Pope Francis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcozzens.html|title=Bishop Andrew H. Cozzens|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> He was consecrated on December 9, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecatholicspirit.com/archdiocese/announcements/auxiliary-bishop-named-archdiocese-saint-paul-minneapolis/|title=Auxiliary bishop named for Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nCozzens and [[Lee A. Pich\u00e9|Lee Pich\u00e9]], both auxiliary bishops of the [[Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]], were involved in an [[John Clayton Nienstedt#Investigations of alleged personal misconduct|investigation of misconduct against Archbishop John Nienstedt]]. The results of the investigation were delivered to [[Carlo Maria Vigan\u00f2]], the [[papal nuncio]] at the time, and no action was taken at the time. Looking back at the investigation, Cozzens said that it was \"doomed to fail\" and different measures were needed for investigations against bishops.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bishop Cozzens: Nienstedt investigation was 'doomed to fail' |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/bishop-cozzens-nienstedt-investigation-was-doomed-to-fail-80491 |website=Catholic News Agency |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[Theodore Edgar McCarrick#Accusations of sexual abuse, investigations, and punishments|McCarrick scandal]] Cozzens has advocated for a national review board made up of both clerical and lay members to investigate allegations of misconduct against bishops.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bishop Cozzens: Nienstedt investigation was 'doomed to fail' |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/bishop-cozzens-nienstedt-investigation-was-doomed-to-fail-80491 |website=Catholic News Agency |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom August\u2013December 2018, he served as the interim rector for the Saint Paul Seminary School of Divinity after Msgr. [[Aloysius R. Callaghan]] retired on August 15 and before Fr. [[Joseph C. Taphorn]] began on January 1, 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|United States}} \n{{Div col}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[Historical list of the Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[List of Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[Lists of patriarchs, archbishops, and bishops]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.archspm.org/ Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis Official Site]\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcozzens.html Catholic-Hierarchy]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|state=collapsed}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cozzens, Andrew}}\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholic bishops]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Denver]]\n[[Category:Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas alumni]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]\n[[Category:Religious leaders from Minnesota]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Colorado]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type        = Bishop\n| honorific-prefix= [[Excellency|His Excellency]], [[The Most Reverend]]\n| name        = Andrew Harmon Cozzens\n| title       = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|Auxiliary Bishop of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]<br>Titular Bishop of [[Africa (Roman province)|Bisica]]\n| image       = Bishop_Cozzens_with_Two_Deacons.jpg\n| alt         = \n| caption     = Bishop Cozzens with two deacons\n| church      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| archdiocese = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]\n| diocese     = \n| see         = \n| appointed   = October 11, 2013\n| enthroned   = December 9, 2013\n| predecessor = \n| successor   =\n| other_post  = Titular Bishop of [[Africa (Roman province)|Bisica]]\n\n<!--   Orders   -->\n| ordination     = May 3, 1997\n| ordinated_by   = \n| consecration   = December 9, 2013\n| consecrated_by = [[John Clayton Nienstedt]], [[Harry Joseph Flynn]], and [[Paul Sirba]]\n| rank           = \n<!--   Personal details   -->\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1968|8|3}}\n| birth_place   = [[Denver, Colorado]] \n| death_date    =\n| death_place   = \n| previous_post =\n| coat_of_arms  = \n| motto         = PR\u00c6BE NOBIS COR TUUM\n}}\n\n{{Infobox bishopstyles  \n| name=  Andrew Harmon Cozzens\n| dipstyle=  \n*[[Excellency|His Excellency]]\n*[[The Most Reverend]]    \n| offstyle=[[Your Excellency]] \n| relstyle=[[Bishop]] \n| image = Coat_of_arms_of_Andrew_Harmon_Cozzens.svg\n| image_size = 200px\n}}\n\n'''Andrew Harmon Cozzens''', (August 3, 1968) is a [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|bishop]] of the [[Catholic Church]] in the [[United States]].  Since 2013 he has been an [[auxiliary bishop]] of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|Saint Paul and Minneapolis]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life and education===\nAndrew Cozzens was born on August 3, 1968, in [[Denver, Colorado]] to Jack and Judy Cozzens.<ref>{{cite web |title=Auxiliary bishop named for Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis |url=http://thecatholicspirit.com/featured/auxiliary-bishop-named-archdiocese-saint-paul-minneapolis/ |website=The Catholic Spirit |publisher=The Catholic Spirit |accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref> Andrew Cozzens attended [[Benedictine College]] in [[Atchison, Kansas]], graduating in 1991.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clawson |first1=Makena |title=Newly elected bishop, Andrew Cozzens, Raven alum \u2013 The Circuit |url=http://benedictinecircuit.com/bishop-elect-andrew-cozzens-raven-bishop/ |website=Benedictine Circuit |accessdate=25 February 2019}}</ref> During his time at Benedictine College, he helped found the college's pro-life student group and a charismatic prayer group. In 1990, he was arrested several times for blocking access to abortion clinics and served several weeks in jail.<ref>{{cite web |title=State v. Cozzens |url=https://law.justia.com/cases/nebraska/supreme-court/1992/494-7.html |website=Justia Law |accessdate=25 February 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wiering |first1=Maria |title=Bishop fields queries on vocations, jail time in Google Hangout |url=http://thecatholicspirit.com/news/local-news/bishop-fields-queries-on-vocations-jail-time-in-google-hangout/ |website=TheCatholicSpirit.com |publisher=The Catholic Spirit |accessdate=25 February 2019 |date=25 November 2015}}</ref> After a period of discernment, including a time serving as a missionary with [[NET Ministries]] in 1991-1992, he entered the [[Saint Paul Seminary School of Divinity]].\n\n===Priestly ministry===\nCozzens was ordained a priest in 1997 for the Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis and served as the associate pastor at the [[Cathedral of Saint Paul (Minnesota)|Cathedral of St. Paul]] from 1997\u20132000 and at Divine Mercy Parish from 2000 to 2002. He earned a S.T.L. from the [[Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas|Pontifical University of St. Thomas Aquinas, ''Angelicum'']] in Rome, Italy in 2002 and began full time doctoral studies in 2002. He earned his S.T.D. in 2008 with a dissertation entitled ''Imago vivens Iesu Christi sponsi Ecclesiae : the priest as a living image of Jesus Christ the Bridegroom of the Church through the evangelical counsels.'' In 2006, he began as an assistant professor of sacramental theology and the director of liturgy at the Saint Paul Seminary School of Divinity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.archspm.org/news-events/news-detail.php?intResourceID=10191|title=Reverend Andrew Cozzens Named Auxiliary Bishop of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> He remained there until he was named a bishop.\n\n===Episcopal ministry===\nCozzens was appointed titular Bishop of Bisica and an auxiliary for the Archbishop of Saint Paul and Minneapolis on October 11, 2013 by [[Pope Francis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcozzens.html|title=Bishop Andrew H. Cozzens|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> He was consecrated on December 9, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecatholicspirit.com/archdiocese/announcements/auxiliary-bishop-named-archdiocese-saint-paul-minneapolis/|title=Auxiliary bishop named for Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nCozzens and [[Lee A. Pich\u00e9|Lee Pich\u00e9]], both auxiliary bishops of the [[Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]], were involved in an [[John Clayton Nienstedt#Investigations of alleged personal misconduct|investigation of misconduct against Archbishop John Nienstedt]]. The results of the investigation were delivered to [[Carlo Maria Vigan\u00f2]], the [[papal nuncio]] at the time, and no action was taken at the time. Looking back at the investigation, Cozzens said that it was \"doomed to fail\" and different measures were needed for investigations against bishops.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bishop Cozzens: Nienstedt investigation was 'doomed to fail' |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/bishop-cozzens-nienstedt-investigation-was-doomed-to-fail-80491 |website=Catholic News Agency |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the [[Theodore Edgar McCarrick#Accusations of sexual abuse, investigations, and punishments|McCarrick scandal]] Cozzens has advocated for a national review board made up of both clerical and lay members to investigate allegations of misconduct against bishops.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bishop Cozzens: Nienstedt investigation was 'doomed to fail' |url=https://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/bishop-cozzens-nienstedt-investigation-was-doomed-to-fail-80491 |website=Catholic News Agency |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFrom August\u2013December 2018, he served as the interim rector for the Saint Paul Seminary School of Divinity after Msgr. [[Aloysius R. Callaghan]] retired on August 15 and before Fr. [[Joseph C. Taphorn]] began on January 1, 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Catholicism|United States}} \n{{Div col}}\n* [[Catholic Church hierarchy]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[Historical list of the Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[List of Catholic bishops of the United States]]\n* [[Lists of patriarchs, archbishops, and bishops]]\n* [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.archspm.org/ Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis Official Site]\n*[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcozzens.html Catholic-Hierarchy]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Saint Paul and Minneapolis|state=collapsed}}\n{{Catholicism}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cozzens, Andrew}}\n[[Category:21st-century Roman Catholic bishops]]\n