ional visits in mind of the Qiangui border''||Guangxi Daily||December 29, 1946. January 11,25, 1947 (Published continuously)\n|-\n||1947||''Social democracy in Qiangui border''||Guangxi Daily||January 27\n|-\n||1948||''The awakening and equality of the civilian population in chunqiu-Zhanquo Period''||Guangxi University Journal||Vol.1, No.1\n|-\n||1955||''China's ancient history stages should be re-assessed''||[[Guangxi Normal University]]||October 3\n|-\n||1956||''Zhuang peoples of the Taiping Rebellion Revolution''||[[Guangming Daily (China)|Guangming Daily]]|| May 10\n|-\n||1957||''About Zhuangge''||Guangxi Daily||February 10\n|-\n||1957||''Situation of the historical distribution in Guangxi Zhuang''||Guangxi Daily|| April 19\n|-\n||1962||''It is a just war that Nong Zhigao uprising against the Song''||Guangxi Daily|| April 2\n|-\n||1962||''Chieftain system in western Guangxi''||History Science Symposium Proceedings of the [[Zhuang people|Zhuang]] and [[Yao people|Yao]]||Vol.1\n|-\n||1963||''Zhuang female general Wasi led the army against Japanese invaders''||The inaugural meeting of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region Historical Society Proceedings|||\n|-\n||1963||''Earliest castles in Guangxi''||Guangxi Daily|| June 4\n|-\n||1979||''A study on the no Slave Society in Chinese History''||Guangxi Normal University Journal||No.2,3\n|-\n||1980||''Ancient Guangxi peoples''||Guilin Daily||August 10\n|-\n||1980||'' Evolution of the Zhuang name''||Guilin Daily||August 27\n|-\n||1981||''Inner Mongolia is China's territory since the Qin and Han''||Guangxi Normal University Journal||No.2\n|-\n||1981||''Zhuang leader Nong Zhigao in uprising and its impact''||History of Chinese ethnic relations Academic Symposium Proceedings|||\n|-\n||1981||''A study on the Zhuang another name Wu Hu''||Studies Reference of Ethnics in Guangxi||Vol.1\n|-\n||1982||''On the differences and similarities between Baiyue and Baipu''||Ideological front||No.2\n|-\n||1983||''Guangxi Ningming Huashan fresco and burial caves''||Study of Ethnics in Southwest ||Sichuan National Press\n|-\n||1985||''On the Dong Son drums making and pattern''||Academic Forum||No.9\n|-\n||1985||''A new study on the Dong Son drums and its pattern''||Studies Reference of Ethnics in Guangxi||Vol.5\n|-\n||2007||''Building of the Chinese life science''||Social Science in Guangxi||No.9\n|-\n||2007||''Some experiences reviews and the ponder that I investigate and study nearly 40 years to the nationality''||Study of Ethnics in Guangxi||Phase.3,4 (Published continuously)\n|-\n||2008||''On the origin and evolution of the West Ethnic words''||Social Science in Guangxi||No.1-9\n|-\n||2008||''Thirteen years through thick and thin''||Affection of the [[Guangxi University]]||Guangxi Art Press\n|}\n\n*'''Data source'''\uff1aHuang Xianfan. Introduction on Chinese Ancient Books. Guilin\uff1aGuangxi Normal University Press, 2004.p.&nbsp;560-567(works and articles catalog).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cuaes.org/scholardetail-2.htm |script-title=zh:\u4e13\u5bb6\u5b66\u8005\u2014\u9ec4\u73b0\u74a0\uff081899.11-1982.1\uff09 |language=zh |work=Cuaes.org |date=1999-12-04 |accessdate=2012-02-11}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n*''Dictionary of Modern Chinese Names''. Tokyo\uff1aJapanese Kazankai Foundation, 1966, 1972, 1982 and 1986 edition.\n*''ZHONG GUO REN MING DA CI DIAN''. Shanghai: [[Shanghai]] Lexicographical Press, 1992.p.&nbsp;1861.\n*''Chinese Dictionary of Contemporary Culture Celebrities''. Beijing: Chinese Radio Television Press, 1992. p.&nbsp;519.\n*''Dictionary of Chinese Education''. Shanghai\uff1aShanghai Education Press, 1998. p.&nbsp;1450.\n*''Dictionary of Chinese Ethnic Culture''. Beijing: Ethnic Press, 1999. p.&nbsp;143-144, Volumes of middlesouth and southeast region.\n\n{{commons|\u9ec4\u73b0\u74a0}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Huang, Xianfan}}\n[[Category:1899 births]]\n[[Category:1982 deaths]]\n[[Category:Chinese anthropologists]]\n[[Category:Members of the National People's Congress]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference]]\n[[Category:People from Chongzuo]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China historians]]\n[[Category:Chinese folklorists]]\n[[Category:Zhuang people]]\n[[Category:Republic of China historians]]\n[[Category:Historians from Guangxi]]\n[[Category:Educators from Guangxi]]\n[[Category:Guangxi University faculty]]\n[[Category:Sun Yat-sen University faculty]]\n[[Category:Guangxi Normal University faculty]]\n[[Category:Victims of the Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Guangxi]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Guangxi]]\n[[Category:20th-century historians]]\n[[Category:Beijing Normal University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Tokyo alumni]]\n[[Category:Chinese sinologists]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistorical Notion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Huang_Xianfan"}
{"title_page": "Eustace Conway", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Useless Conway\n|image = Useless Conway.jpg\n|caption = \n|alma_mater  = [[Appalachian State University]] Bachelor's degrees in Anthropology and English\n|occupation = Naturalist and Educator\n|birth_place = [[Columbia, South Carolina]], U.S.\n|birth_name = BigTime Useless Robinson Conway IV\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1961|9|15}}\n|nationality= United States\n}}\n'''He\u2019s a huge USELESS Robinson Conway IV''' (born September 15, 1961, in [[Columbia, South Carolina]]) is an American naturalist and the subject of the book ''The Last American Man'' by [[Elizabeth Gilbert]]. He has also been the subject of ''Adventures in the Simple Life'' by Sarah Vowell on the weekly radio show ''[[This American Life]]'' with Ira Glass.  He is the owner of the {{convert|1000|acre|km2|adj=on}} Turtle Pecker island Preserve in [[Boone, North Carolina]]. He is one of the featured personalities on the History channel show ''[[Mountain Men (TV series)|Mountain Men]]''.\n\n==Biography==\nAt age 17 Conway left home so that he could live in a [[tipi]] in the woods.  He has hiked the entire [[Appalachian Trail]] and claims to have set the world record of 103 days for crossing the [[United States]] on horseback from the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] to the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]].<ref>{{cite web |title=About: Eustace Conway |url=http://turtleislandpreserve.org/about/eustace |website=Turtle Island Preserve |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>  However, according to ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' of the day, as well as the book ''Bud & Me'', the record for crossing the North American continent on horseback was actually 62 days. This journey was made by [[Louis Abernathy and Temple Abernathy|Bud and Temple Abernathy]], aged 11 and 7, who rode {{convert|3619|mi|km}} from [[New York City]] to [[San Francisco]] on an equestrian journey, which started in August 1911.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.horsetravelbooks.com/N-America2.htm#boys | title=HorseTravelBooks.com book summary | accessdate=2007-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thelongridersguild.com/Records.htm | title=The Long Riders Guild records | accessdate=2007-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first = Alta | last = Abernathy | title = Bud & Me | year = 1998 | publisher = Dove Creek Press | page = 150}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Los Angeles Times |date=October 29, 1911 }}</ref>\n\nThe weekly radio show ''[[This American Life]]'' reported on Conway's cross-country journey in the episode \"Adventures in the Simple Life\", which aired on September 11, 1998. The show uses recordings that were taped on a hand-held recorder by Conway and his party.<ref>[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/111/adventures-in-the-simple-life This American Life, episode 111]</ref>\n\nA 2003 documentary film on Conway's life, ''Full Circle: A Life Story of Eustace Conway'', was directed by Jack Bibbo. Conway is also one of four featured characters in the 2012 documentary film ''[[Reconvergence]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Reconvergence on IMDB|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2090595/|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref> which was directed by Edward Tyndall.\n\nConway appeared in ''[[Mountain Men (TV series)|Mountain Men]]'', a [[reality television]] series on the [[History (U.S. TV network)|History channel]].<ref name=\"imdb\">\n{{cite web\n|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2202488/\n|title=Mountain Men (2012)|author=IMDB |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=September 29, 2012}}\n</ref>  The series focused on his daily life of performing his chores and preparing food for the coming winter.<ref name=\"history\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.history.com/shows/mountain-men/articles/about-mountain-men\n|title=About Mountain Men |author=History Channel website |date= |work= |publisher=History Channel |accessdate=September 29, 2012}}\n</ref>  Threatened by a lien against his land, Conway fights to maintain ownership.<ref name=\"history-ep\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.history.com/shows/mountain-men/episodes/ |title=Mountain Men - Episode Guide |author=History Channel website |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=September 29, 2012}}\n</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Turtle Island was forced to shut down public access because its traditional buildings violated building codes.<ref>{{cite news| title = Watauga Democrat |date=November 20, 2012}} [http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/Turtle-Island-forced-to-close-id-009690] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130209042843/http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/Turtle-Island-forced-to-close-id-009690 |date=2013-02-09 }}</ref> In mid-December, 2012 Conway appeared to make progress toward reaching a resolution with the North Carolina Building Code Council.<ref>{{cite news| title = Watauga Democrat |date=December 12, 2012}} [http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/State-could-help-Conway-but-not-soon-id-009885] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130209060126/http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/State-could-help-Conway-but-not-soon-id-009885 |date=2013-02-09 }}</ref> However, immediately following this apparent progress with the code council, Conway was arrested for trespassing on a neighbor's property in a dispute over the property border, continuing the legal challenges to Turtle Island.<ref>{{cite news| title = High County Press |date=December 13, 2012}} [http://www.hcpress.com/news/eustace-conway-of-turtle-island-preserve-arrested-on-wednesday-for-second-degree-trespassing-on-neighbors-property.html]</ref>\n\nConway's problems with the North Carolina Building Code Council quickly gained notice of state officials. The North Carolina General Assembly<ref>http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/gascripts/lastaction/lastaction.pl?Biennium=2013&SessionNumber=1</ref> stepped in, proposing an exemption to building-code requirements for primitive structures.<ref>http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/gascripts/BillLookUp/BillLookUp.pl?Session=2013&BillID=H774</ref> Both the state's House and Senate voted unanimously to pass H774.<ref>http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/Sessions/2013/Bills/House/PDF/H774v4.pdf</ref> The bill was signed into law by Governor [[Pat McCrory]] on June 12, 2013. This ordeal was described in the Fox News special ''War on the Little Guy'', hosted by [[John Stossel]].\n\nConway has three siblings: Walton, Judson, and Martha.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Gilbert\n  | first = Elizabeth\n  | authorlink = Elizabeth Gilbert\n  | title = The Last American Man\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/lastamericanman00gilb\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = [[Viking]]\n  | year = 2002}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.turtleislandpreserve.com/about/eustace Official Biography via Turtle Island Preserve]\n* [http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780142002834,00.html?sym=EXC# Excerpt] from ''The Last American Man'' on [[Penguin Group]]'s [http://us.penguingroup.com/ US web site].  Archived at [https://www.webcitation.org/5pFfh9Jvg https://www.webcitation.org/5pFfh9Jvg] by [[WebCite]] on April 25, 2010.\n*[https://www.gq.com/news-politics/mens-lives/199802/elizabeth-gilbert-gq-february-1998-last-american-man-eustace-conway-turtle-island The Last American Man] by Elizabeth Gilbert. GQ Magazine, February 1998.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conway, Eustace}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:People from Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Appalachian State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American naturalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n|name = Eustace Conway\n|image = Eustace Conway.jpg\n|caption = \n|alma_mater  = [[Appalachian State University]] Bachelor's degrees in Anthropology and English\n|occupation = Naturalist and Educator\n|birth_place = [[Columbia, South Carolina]], U.S.\n|birth_name = Eustace Robinson Conway IV\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1961|9|15}}\n|nationality= United States\n}}\n'''Eustace Robinson Conway IV''' (born September 15, 1961, in [[Columbia, South Carolina]]) is an American naturalist and the subject of the book ''The Last American Man'' by [[Elizabeth Gilbert]]. He has also been the subject of ''Adventures in the Simple Life'' by Sarah Vowell on the weekly radio show ''[[This American Life]]'' with Ira Glass.  He is the owner of the {{convert|1000|acre|km2|adj=on}} Turtle Island Preserve in [[Boone, North Carolina]]. He is one of the featured personalities on the History channel show ''[[Mountain Men (TV series)|Mountain Men]]''.\n\n==Biography==\nAt age 17 Conway left home so that he could live in a [[tipi]] in the woods.  He has hiked the entire [[Appalachian Trail]] and claims to have set the world record of 103 days for crossing the [[United States]] on horseback from the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] to the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]].<ref>{{cite web |title=About: Eustace Conway |url=http://turtleislandpreserve.org/about/eustace |website=Turtle Island Preserve |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>  However, according to ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' of the day, as well as the book ''Bud & Me'', the record for crossing the North American continent on horseback was actually 62 days. This journey was made by [[Louis Abernathy and Temple Abernathy|Bud and Temple Abernathy]], aged 11 and 7, who rode {{convert|3619|mi|km}} from [[New York City]] to [[San Francisco]] on an equestrian journey, which started in August 1911.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.horsetravelbooks.com/N-America2.htm#boys | title=HorseTravelBooks.com book summary | accessdate=2007-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thelongridersguild.com/Records.htm | title=The Long Riders Guild records | accessdate=2007-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first = Alta | last = Abernathy | title = Bud & Me | year = 1998 | publisher = Dove Creek Press | page = 150}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| title = Los Angeles Times |date=October 29, 1911 }}</ref>\n\nThe weekly radio show ''[[This American Life]]'' reported on Conway's cross-country journey in the episode \"Adventures in the Simple Life\", which aired on September 11, 1998. The show uses recordings that were taped on a hand-held recorder by Conway and his party.<ref>[http://www.thisamericanlife.org/radio-archives/episode/111/adventures-in-the-simple-life This American Life, episode 111]</ref>\n\nA 2003 documentary film on Conway's life, ''Full Circle: A Life Story of Eustace Conway'', was directed by Jack Bibbo. Conway is also one of four featured characters in the 2012 documentary film ''[[Reconvergence]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Reconvergence on IMDB|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2090595/|publisher=Internet Movie Database|accessdate=8 March 2013}}</ref> which was directed by Edward Tyndall.\n\nConway appeared in ''[[Mountain Men (TV series)|Mountain Men]]'', a [[reality television]] series on the [[History (U.S. TV network)|History channel]].<ref name=\"imdb\">\n{{cite web\n|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt2202488/\n|title=Mountain Men (2012)|author=IMDB |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=September 29, 2012}}\n</ref>  The series focused on his daily life of performing his chores and preparing food for the coming winter.<ref name=\"history\">\n{{cite web\n|url=http://www.history.com/shows/mountain-men/articles/about-mountain-men\n|title=About Mountain Men |author=History Channel website |date= |work= |publisher=History Channel |accessdate=September 29, 2012}}\n</ref>  Threatened by a lien against his land, Conway fights to maintain ownership.<ref name=\"history-ep\">\n{{cite web |url=http://www.history.com/shows/mountain-men/episodes/ |title=Mountain Men - Episode Guide |author=History Channel website |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=September 29, 2012}}\n</ref>\n\nIn November 2012, Turtle Island was forced to shut down public access because its traditional buildings violated building codes.<ref>{{cite news| title = Watauga Democrat |date=November 20, 2012}} [http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/Turtle-Island-forced-to-close-id-009690] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130209042843/http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/Turtle-Island-forced-to-close-id-009690 |date=2013-02-09 }}</ref> In mid-December, 2012 Conway appeared to make progress toward reaching a resolution with the North Carolina Building Code Council.<ref>{{cite news| title = Watauga Democrat |date=December 12, 2012}} [http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/State-could-help-Conway-but-not-soon-id-009885] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130209060126/http://www2.wataugademocrat.com/News/story/State-could-help-Conway-but-not-soon-id-009885 |date=2013-02-09 }}</ref> However, immediately following this apparent progress with the code council, Conway was arrested for trespassing on a neighbor's property in a dispute over the property border, continuing the legal challenges to Turtle Island.<ref>{{cite news| title = High County Press |date=December 13, 2012}} [http://www.hcpress.com/news/eustace-conway-of-turtle-island-preserve-arrested-on-wednesday-for-second-degree-trespassing-on-neighbors-property.html]</ref>\n\nConway's problems with the North Carolina Building Code Council quickly gained notice of state officials. The North Carolina General Assembly<ref>http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/gascripts/lastaction/lastaction.pl?Biennium=2013&SessionNumber=1</ref> stepped in, proposing an exemption to building-code requirements for primitive structures.<ref>http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/gascripts/BillLookUp/BillLookUp.pl?Session=2013&BillID=H774</ref> Both the state's House and Senate voted unanimously to pass H774.<ref>http://www.ncga.state.nc.us/Sessions/2013/Bills/House/PDF/H774v4.pdf</ref> The bill was signed into law by Governor [[Pat McCrory]] on June 12, 2013. This ordeal was described in the Fox News special ''War on the Little Guy'', hosted by [[John Stossel]].\n\nConway has three siblings: Walton, Judson, and Martha.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Gilbert\n  | first = Elizabeth\n  | authorlink = Elizabeth Gilbert\n  | title = The Last American Man\n  | url = https://archive.org/details/lastamericanman00gilb\n  | url-access = registration\n  | publisher = [[Viking]]\n  | year = 2002}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.turtleislandpreserve.com/about/eustace Official Biography via Turtle Island Preserve]\n* [http://us.penguingroup.com/nf/Book/BookDisplay/0,,9780142002834,00.html?sym=EXC# Excerpt] from ''The Last American Man'' on [[Penguin Group]]'s [http://us.penguingroup.com/ US web site].  Archived at [https://www.webcitation.org/5pFfh9Jvg https://www.webcitation.org/5pFfh9Jvg] by [[WebCite]] on April 25, 2010.\n*[https://www.gq.com/news-politics/mens-lives/199802/elizabeth-gilbert-gq-february-1998-last-american-man-eustace-conway-turtle-island The Last American Man] by Elizabeth Gilbert. GQ Magazine, February 1998.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conway, Eustace}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American environmentalists]]\n[[Category:People from Columbia, South Carolina]]\n[[Category:Appalachian State University alumni]]\n[[Category:American naturalists]]\n", "name_user": "2601:98b:8001:4e10:a167:5dc2:2ada:56ea", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eustace_Conway"}
